## Frameworks for web development 
## What are frameworks?
-> Web development frameworks are much like packaged libraries that provide developers with
management and build capabilities. These frameworks are stand-alone packages with built-in predefined services which can be used to build robust web applications.

Advantages of frameworks
1. Allows for rapid application development.
2. Existing services can easily be integrated with the build environment.
3. More lean code base.

Disadvantages of frameworks
1. Build environment is prone to major updates, which forces developers to maintain code base.
2. Includes a learning curve in instances where new programming languages are required.
3. Integration is not guaranteed with all platforms. 

### Front-end frameworks
## Vue.js
-> Vue.js is one of the newest web development frameworks to be adopted among web developers. Its
open source architecture is highly favoured. The framework is extremely robust in that the design of
user-interfaces can easily reflect changes in real-time data that is often served on the back-end.
Components in Vue.js are self-contained and highly reusable throughout the application lifecycle.

## Angular
Angular was developed and is maintained by Google, it is one of the most popular web development
frameworks among developers. Angular uses TypeScript instead of JavaScript as an object-orientated
programming language, however being familiar with JavaScript does make it a lot easier to learn
TypeScript from the ground up. Angular projects are neatly packaged and structured into components,
services and modules. If web based applications require really good performance, Angular is certainly worth considering as a framework.

## React JS
React is a framework developed by Facebook. It is widely popular for its use in building responsive user-interfaces. React elements are the building blocks of creating web applications much like the DOM model is the essence of HTML. The framework adopts JavaScript XML to create elements which is an
extension of JavaScript. 

### Back-end frameworks
## Firebase
Firebase is back-end platform developed by Google, for both mobile and web applications. It provides
an array of back-end services which includes storage, real-time databases and machine learning
capabilities. Firebase is a very affordable solution for developers who require a back-end service that is scalable for small and medium sized projects. Unlike a SQL database, Firebase makes use of an unstructured database, also known as a NoSQL database.

## MongoDB
MongoDB is an open source NoSQL database that uses documents to store data. Much like Firebase,
MongoDB is ideal for unstructured data sets that can be queried using key-value pairs. MongoDB also
offers developers real-time data analytics and visualisation.
## AWS
AWS offers a wide variety of digital services for developers. One notable back-end service for web
developers include the Amazon Relational Database Service (RDS). For developers who prefer to use a
SQL database hosted on the cloud, RDS is a great alternative.